After the changes merged in #842, `sfxGetAvailableDevices` becomes very broken. This is due to the use of `Con::getReturnBuffer` both to [store an intermediate result](https://github.com/GarageGames/Torque3D/blob/development/Engine/source/sfx/sfxSystem.cpp#L1256) and [when converting types](https://github.com/GarageGames/Torque3D/blob/81a385094fa270a4838b801e49d143ef61ef2b58/Engine/source/console/consoleTypes.cpp#L395), which happens inside `Con::getIntArg`.

An easy solution would be to use a `StringBuilder` or `std::string` for intermediate results, and then only use `Con::getReturnBuffer` at the end of the function call. However there may be other instances of this error, and it might be nice to fix the system's reliance on the global mutable `Con::mArgBuffer` in both these functions.

@Azaezel, @jamesu

It can be used client or server side.

This is useful when you want to be notified every X ticks that an object processes.

Usages: Rotating an object every so many ticks, tracking spell recycles, etc.

Example:

Where you create your player object add:
%player.EnableCounters = true;
%player.TickCounterAdd("TestCounter",100);

Then add
function Player::onTickCounter(%this,%counterName)
{
   echo("--------->" @ %counterName);
}

It has several functions
-TickCounterAdd
-TickCounterRemove
-TickCounterGetInterval
-TickCounterReset
-TickCounterHas
-TickCounterSuspend
-TickCountersClear
